## Insurance and Financial Responsibility Requirements

Insurance requirements for private transportation create another layer of safety standards that operate through financial incentives rather than direct safety regulation. Insurance companies conduct their own risk assessments and safety requirements that often exceed regulatory minimums, but coverage quality and claims handling procedures vary significantly between insurance providers and policy types.

Liability insurance minimums vary significantly between jurisdictions and vehicle types. Federal regulations require $1.5 million coverage for vehicles carrying up to fifteen passengers, but some states have lower requirements and others mandate higher coverage. Local jurisdictions often impose additional insurance requirements that exceed state and federal minimums, particularly for airport operations.

Commercial auto insurance for passenger transportation includes coverage types that don't exist in standard auto policies. Garage keeper's liability covers passenger belongings, general liability covers boarding and disembarking injuries, and passenger accident insurance provides medical coverage regardless of fault determination. Coverage comprehensiveness varies significantly between policies and insurance providers.

Self-insurance programs allow larger companies to assume financial responsibility for claims rather than purchasing traditional insurance. Self-insurance requires financial reserves and regulatory approval, but it can provide better claims handling and coverage than commercial insurance. However, self-insured companies create different risk profiles for passengers because protection depends entirely on company financial stability.

